  "prompt": "U.S. Immigration: Can an H1-B visa be extended by future employers beyond 6 years based on an approved I-140 through the previous employer?",
  "response": "Yes, an H-1B visa can be extended beyond the standard 6-year limit if the beneficiary (the H-1B holder) has an approved **I-140 petition** from a previous employer, even if they are now working for a different employer. This extension is possible under the **American Competitiveness in the Twenty-First Century Act (AC21)**. Here\u2019s how it works:\n\n### Key Points for Extending H-1B Beyond 6 Years:\n1. **Approved I-140 from a Previous Employer**:\n   - If the H-1B holder has an I-140 petition approved by a previous employer, they are eligible for **H-1B extensions in 3-year increments** beyond the 6-year limit, even if they are now working for a different employer.\n   - The I-140 does not need to have been filed by the current employer.\n\n2. **No Withdrawal of the I-140**:\n   - The approved I-140 must not have been withdrawn or revoked by the previous employer. If the I-140 remains valid (unwithdrawn), the H-1B holder can still qualify for extensions.\n\n3. **PERM Labor Certification Filed 365 Days Before H-1B Expiration**:\n   - If the H-1B holder\u2019s current employer has filed a PERM labor certification or an I-140 petition on their behalf at least **365 days before the H-1B expires**, they may also qualify for H-1B extensions beyond the 6-year limit.\n\n4. **Cap-Exempt Status**:\n   - Extensions beyond the 6-year limit are not subject to the H-1B cap, meaning they can be filed at any time without waiting for the annual cap period.\n\n### Practical Steps:\n- The new employer must file an **H-1B extension petition** with U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS).\n- The petition should include evidence of the approved I-140 (from the previous employer) or proof that a PERM or I-140 has been pending for at least 365 days (from the current employer).\n\n### Important Considerations:\n- If the I-140 is withdrawn or revoked, the H-1B holder may lose eligibility for extensions beyond 6 years unless they have a new I-140 approved or a PERM pending for 365 days.\n- The H-1B holder must maintain valid H-1B status and ensure all filings are timely.\n\nThis provision allows H-1B workers to continue working in the U.S. while waiting for their priority date to become current for green card processing, even if they change employers. Always consult with an immigration attorney to ensure compliance with USCIS requirements.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
